  "title" : "Get generated sequence after insert with JDBC",
  "body" : "<p>We have a Java database abstraction that does a number of inserts for us.  At runtime we'll know the table name, the column names to insert and the values.  From that we generate a prepared statement and do the insert.</p>\n<p>In SQL Server land we would tack on <code>select id = @@identity</code> to the end of the generated SQL to get the newly generated id returned by the query.</p>\n<p>Now that we're migrating to PostgreSQL, this no longer works.  It's my understanding that in PostgreSQL you can do:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-sql prettyprint-override\"><code>insert into foo(a, b) values('a', 'b') returning ID\n</code></pre>\n<p>Our problem is that at runtime we don't know the name of the ID column nor do we know the name of the sequence.  Is there any way to generically get the value of the newly inserted sequence without knowing the name of the sequence or the name of the column?</p>\n"
}